    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Austin Riley** (72.25) stands as our premier offensive anchor. Facing Jake Irvin, **Riley** benefits from a high-upside matchup against a sub-5.00 xERA starter, combined with the favorable hitting conditions that push him well into the \u201cStrong\u201d tier. Similarly, **James Wood** (69.33) is a priority start. Leading off against Bryce Elder provides him the best opportunity to maximize his counting stats, and his 10% order bonus makes him a foundational piece for our Roto output today. While **Tyler Soderstrom** (65.09) faces a tougher park adjustment, he remains a high-floor play against Emerson Hancock, capitalizing on the SP\u2019s vulnerability to generate scoring potential in the middle of our lineup.\n\nWe are navigating a cluster of high-50s scores, forcing some difficult choices. **Alex Freeland** (60.02) narrowly cracks the start over the rest of the bench, largely because the matchup against Jose Quintana offers such a substantial park and pitcher-skill boost that it overrides the negative impact of batting in the 9-hole. Conversely, **Kyle Karros** (44.18) is the most notable exclusion from today\u2019s lineup. While he benefits from the same favorable park and the slow delivery of Justin Wrobleski, his position in the bottom of the order and the lack of a strong platoon advantage keep him firmly behind our core starters. We continue to monitor the status of **Corbin Carroll**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Jose Caballero**, all of whom are sidelined today; their absence necessitates that we lean on the depth of **Max Muncy** (57.87) and **Trevor Story** (56.73) to stabilize our counting categories.\n\nRisk management remains a primary focus, as the majority of our lineup is currently marked \"Lineup Pending.\" **Mickey Moniak** (48.48) is a particular point of concern; despite the favorable park and the potential to exploit a slow delivery from Justin Wrobleski, his performance is heavily hampered by a double-digit platoon penalty. We must also stay vigilant regarding the defensive capabilities of opposing catchers and elite hold SPs, which are currently dragging down the scoring projections for both **Seiya Suzuki** (53.09) and **Max Muncy**. As we look toward the rest of the week, the continued lack of availability from key speedsters like **Brice Turang**, **Carson Williams**, and **Zach McKinstry** places a high premium on **James Wood** and **Alex Freeland** to maintain our competitive edge in the stolen base category.",
